From: negativo17 <build@negativo17.org>
Date: Thu, 9 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Add libcamhal pipeline handler for Intel IPU cameras

Adds a "libcamhal" pipeline handler that exposes Intel IPU (IPU6/IPU7/IPU8)
cameras through the proprietary libcamhal HAL, the same path icamerasrc uses,
giving full Intel imaging (3A/tuning) instead of libcamera's software ISP.

The HAL is dlopen()'d with RTLD_LOCAL rather than linked: linking it globally
would interpose the platform plugin's logging globals and crash on the first
HAL log (this is why icamerasrc, which loads the HAL locally, never crashes).

libcamhal exists only on x86_64, so the pipeline is enabled there only. Both it
and the software-ISP "simple" handler are built; to avoid a duplicate camera,
"simple" calls camhal_available() (a dlopen-only check) and yields the Intel
IPU media devices (intel-ipu6/intel-ipu7) to libcamhal when it is installed,
gated on the HAVE_PIPELINE_LIBCAMHAL config.h define. If libcamhal is absent it
falls through to the software ISP unchanged.

Buffers are re-queued with their sequence/timestamp reset (as icamerasrc does),
without which the HAL's bookkeeping is corrupted and ISYS stalls after the
buffers cycle once.

By default only camera 0 (the primary bound sensor) is registered, since the
HAL enumerates every configured sensor slot regardless of presence; set
LIBCAMERA_CAMHAL_CAMERAS=all (or an id) to override.
diff --git a/meson.build b/meson.build
index e86a4f7..5ba450b 100644
--- a/meson.build
+++ b/meson.build
@@ -217,6 +217,9 @@ arch_x86 = ['x86', 'x86_64']
 pipelines_support = {
     'imx8-isi':     arch_arm,
     'ipu3':         arch_x86,
+    # libcamhal (the proprietary Intel IPU HAL) is only available on x86_64, so
+    # restrict to it rather than arch_x86 (which would include i686).
+    'libcamhal':    ['x86_64'],
     'mali-c55':     arch_arm,
     'rkisp1':       arch_arm,
     #'rpi/pisp':     arch_arm,
@@ -252,6 +255,13 @@ if get_option('test')
     endforeach
 endif
 
+# When the libcamhal pipeline handler is built, let the "simple" handler detect
+# libcamhal at runtime and yield Intel IPU devices to it (so the software-ISP
+# duplicate does not appear alongside the HAL camera).
+if pipelines.contains('libcamhal')
+    config_h.set('HAVE_PIPELINE_LIBCAMHAL', 1)
+endif
+
 # Utilities are parsed first to provide support for other components.
 subdir('utils')
 
